latestPosts.caption: Recently I was angry enough to want my brother dead‚Ä¶
I kind of miss male attention.

‚ÄúHe was more than my brother; he was my best friend. I wanted to be him. He was more athletic, had more friends, got more girls. And things were going great for him. He was managing a pizza place. He had two kids, my nephews. But after he lost his job he started dealing drugs. He didn‚Äôt last two months in the streets. Benjamin thought the world was like our family; he was too trusting of people. And Detroit is a very dangerous place to be trusting of people. The Detroit Police Department did nothing: no leads, no investigation. It‚Äôs like he wasn‚Äôt even human. You can just murder people in that city. After his death I forgot about school. I dropped my classes, started drinking more, partying more. There was a lot of sex, a lot of meaningless sex. Nothing seemed to matter. It was dark. I was so angry at God, because how could he let that happen? But it‚Äôs been four years now. And looking back‚Äîif he hadn‚Äôt been killed, so many other things don‚Äôt happen. I‚Äôd have never left Detroit. Benjamin was the one who always told me: ‚ÄòYou‚Äôre special. You don‚Äôt have to stay here.‚Äô But if he hadn‚Äôt been killed, I‚Äôd have never come to New York. And if I don‚Äôt come to New York, I don‚Äôt meet my best friend, which is my wife. Our wedding brought my whole family together for the first time since Benjamin‚Äôs death. It was love and joy again. My mom walking me down the aisle, after losing her son. It just meant the world to her. And if I hadn‚Äôt met my wife, we wouldn‚Äôt have a son on the way. We‚Äôre naming him Benjamin.‚Äù

latestPosts.caption: ‚ÄúFinding time for them, that‚Äôs the hardest part. For my Autistic son especially; because he‚Äôs the one that needs me the most. I work full time. And as soon as my work schedule stops, my mom schedule starts. I‚Äôm on the way to pick them up right now. I know the bond is there. Oh my God; they‚Äôre so attached to me. But I feel like they only get to see the strict mom, the military mom. The school is always asking us to do more academic things with them. So it‚Äôs a lot of: let‚Äôs do homework, let‚Äôs read books. Then after that it‚Äôs: we have to eat, we have to take a shower, we have to go to bed. And let‚Äôs do it fast. Because you need to get to sleep. You need your rest, because we have so much to do tomorrow. I feel like what I‚Äôm missing most, at this moment, is fun. There‚Äôs no time for fun. I don‚Äôt want them to only see me as a mother. I want them to see me as a friend, a best friend. Someone who will do crazy stuff with them. I heard that it might rain today. So I‚Äôm hoping, really hoping, that we get caught in the rain today.‚Äù

latestPosts.caption: ‚ÄúMy mom was a witch. Now she‚Äôs a Norse Pagan. I think she just finds the whitest religion she can possibly believe in. It‚Äôs like: alright Carol, do your thing. I‚Äôm here to support you. Then I have an edgelord older brother, who‚Äôs all: ‚ÄòI‚Äôm a Satanist.‚Äô OK, Andrew. Let‚Äôs calm down. My dad is more of a Mexican Catholic Guy. He just copes. He‚Äôs really banking on the whole last rites thing, so he‚Äôs kinda sorted. Honestly, I wish I was religious. At least they have something. Because for me it‚Äôs like: ‚ÄòOh shit, there‚Äôs nothing next.‚Äô And that doesn‚Äôt sound nice. But ultimately life is just a series of chemical reactions, which is a depressing way of thinking about it. But I mean, I‚Äôm pretty sure that‚Äôs what‚Äôs happening here. Even these thoughts‚Äîthey‚Äôre just a series of chemical reactions, and one day the reactions end, and you can‚Äôt think anymore. I don‚Äôt even want to think about it. My therapist was like: ‚ÄòYou should really stop thinking about it.‚Äô I‚Äôve actually chilled out a lot from when I was at my worst. Here‚Äôs something I use to comfort myself: ultimately my body is going to decay and I‚Äôll get recycled back into the earth, right? And maybe a mushroom will spring up from my body. That‚Äôs a new form of something-or-other. And when the Earth finally comes to an end‚Äî my molecules will still be there, in some form. Just floating through the universe, forever. So that‚Äôs nice, I guess. That‚Äôs a comforting thought.‚Äù

latestPosts.caption: ‚ÄúHe was a mentor. The leader of a huge religious organization: intelligent, charismatic. Everyone respected him. I was a teenage girl. My father traveled a lot. I never had any boyfriends. I wanted affection. And for him to give me attention, it was like‚ÄîI wanted that. I did want it. I wanted him to look at me. I would dress for him. It makes me sick to think about now, but I would choose my clothes solely to make him look at me. I wanted him to say that I was pretty. I wanted his attention. And because I wanted it at first, you know‚ÄîI felt like I gave myself to this person willingly. That‚Äôs why I didn‚Äôt report it for so many years. Because I felt like I was tempting him. He waited until I turned eighteen. And every time he abused me, he encouraged me to share the responsibility. He used the word ‚Äòwe.‚Äô Always ‚Äòwe.‚Äô He‚Äôd say: ‚ÄòWe‚Äôre not supposed to be doing this. You‚Äôre making me do this. I don‚Äôt want to, but you‚Äôre making me do this.‚Äô Every time it was over, he‚Äôd say: ‚ÄòNow go to church and confess. Confess to tempting an older man.‚Äô I sued him last year, thanks to the Adult Survivors Act. I expected him to fight it tooth and nail; deny everything. But a couple days ago he sent a statement to my lawyer, basically apologizing for everything. When I got the letter, I thought of the child me. All I did in my mind was hug that child. It‚Äôs like: you can forgive yourself now. There was never any ‚Äòwe.‚Äô He knew you didn‚Äôt have a father figure. He knew how you‚Äôd respond to the attention. He knew how you‚Äôd respond to the guilt, and the shame. He knew everything. It may have felt like you were choosing, but you weren‚Äôt. You were chosen.‚Äù

latestPosts.caption: ‚ÄúIt‚Äôs a miracle I‚Äôm even here. My father went through World War II: the Normandy Invasion, Omaha Beach. So for him to survive all that, and live long enough to become my father‚Äîit‚Äôs a miraculous thing. He died before I was eight years old. But it was enough time to experience him deeply. I was very loved, very welcomed, very cared for: my parents were thrilled I was their child. When I was younger I traveled quite a bit. Not every place, but a lot of places: Greece, Turkey, Alaska. And this wasn‚Äôt just going on tours. It was real, vagabond stuff: no reservations, no plans. Just deeply experiencing another culture and another place. I‚Äôve gotten to do every kind of work, from agricultural labor to factory work. For twenty years I was a social worker with seniors. But I can‚Äôt even call that a job, it was a service. I got to take care of people: bring them meals, help with housekeeping. It was an absolute calling. I was a workaholic. And now that I‚Äôm retired‚Äî I‚Äôm a play-aholic. There‚Äôs nonstop free music in New York. I come to this park to listen to jazz piano. I go to Juilliard to listen to student recitals. There‚Äôs going to be a Dixieland ragtime ensemble near Macy‚Äôs. I mean, it‚Äôs endless. I‚Äôm just grateful for good health to enjoy it all. So many people wake up in pain. But I have my health, and I have a home. I mean, it‚Äôs not a home. But I have a place. A safe place to rent. It‚Äôs just been a blessed, beautiful life. The perfect life for me. I found it very, very rich. Very deep. And I think all of it was a blessing. All of it, miracles and blessings.‚Äù

latestPosts.caption: ‚ÄúIt‚Äôs going on seven years now. I was functioning until I lost my apartment, then my job. I was living with this one couple for a while but they kicked me out. But I try not to think about how long it‚Äôs been. I‚Äôve read books about heroin addicts who changed their lives around twenty-six, so you know. I‚Äôm still young. I just want to get back to my life. I‚Äôm tired of waking up and needing it to not feel sick. I‚Äôm tired of being homeless. I want to start talking to my family again; that‚Äôs the biggest, I think. The not speaking to my parents. I missed my mom‚Äôs birthday. And my sister‚Äôs birthday; just two days ago. I really am blessed with a good family. I mean, my parents were strict; but I can‚Äôt blame that anymore. I‚Äôve been trying to figure out the source of it. I think part of me just wanted to try everything. You know: what‚Äôs it like? But I think there was another part of me that wanted the attention, I guess. Something I could do so that people would like, ask me: are you ok? Some way to share the pain. I tried to kill myself once, when I was fourteen. I don‚Äôt know; I had such a good life. I was just so mad at myself for being so sad.‚Äù

latestPosts.caption: ‚ÄúI‚Äôm on the ‚Äòwhat the fuck is going on‚Äô path. And I‚Äôve been on the case for awhile. We‚Äôre this animal that learned how to communicate. We became vicious. We‚Äôre making a mess, trying to learn how to not murder each other. We‚Äôve almost got it. Sometimes things happen, still. But we‚Äôve come this far, and we didn‚Äôt come with a manual, right? So we‚Äôre trying to figure this out. We‚Äôve cut down on it. We‚Äôre doing great.‚Äù

latestPosts.caption: ‚ÄúNobody taught me. There were so many of us in the house, and even my Nanna didn‚Äôt know how to read. So I never learned to read. I was so bad at school that I acted like a clown just to avoid everything; then I got caught running around here with a pistol when I was thirteen. They sent me to Tryon Juvenile Detention Center, and that‚Äôs where I met Ms. Lakewood. She taught the computer class. Heavy-set Italian lady, about 4‚Äô 10‚Äù. But attitude, huge. Aura, big. She was like the grandmother in a mob movie. You know how you‚Äôve got all the bosses, but when the grandmother comes in‚Äîeveryone shuts up? She was like that. But she was loving too. She had pictures on the wall of all her favorite students; she called them her babies. She even had a picture of Mike Tyson up there. He was one of her babies. One day we had this contest, on the computer. The winner got $50. And I was looking at the screen and getting so angry. I‚Äôm crying, because I couldn‚Äôt read. And that‚Äôs when this Spanish kid called me Forrest Gump. He had the whole class laughing at me. Miss Lakewood was like: ‚ÄòWhat‚Äôs going on?‚Äô She came over to me and said: ‚ÄòFix your face. Fix your fucking face, I don‚Äôt want to see another tear.‚Äô Then she said: ‚ÄòTomorrow, you better get ready.‚Äô She started working with me for an hour-and-a-half, every night. She started me on Lion King. It was a preschool book, so I didn‚Äôt want to do it. But she made me. Every night she made me keep reading until I was able to read on my grade level. I started getting report cards with nothing less than 85. I was sending them home; my mom was getting hyped. I got my GED. I started reading so much. Today I can finish a five-hundred-page book in two days. If I smoke a blunt first, I swear to God I can picture the whole book like it‚Äôs a movie. Miss Lakewood passed away when I was eighteen. I heard about it while I was in prison. Some new guys came in; they‚Äôd been in Tryon too. They heard me talking about her and that‚Äôs when one of them told me. But he said: ‚ÄòYo. I‚Äôm pretty sure she had your picture on the wall.‚Äô‚Äù

latestPosts.caption: ‚ÄúI was seventeen. Only child, not a lot of friends. But I had a plan. I was going to become an actress, get a role on All My Children, meet my husband on set‚Äî and when that was all over‚ÄîI‚Äôd host a talk show. Kelly Ripa did it; I could do it too. Back then it seemed like every woman on television had gotten their start as beauty queen. So my senior year I decided to enter my school‚Äôs Homecoming Queen competition. It was organized like a Ms. America pageant. But this was a rough high school, only one other girl signed up‚Äî so I had a good shot. My whole family got behind me. My mom was a seamstress. We noticed that in most pageants we watched, the winner wore a white dress. So she sewed me a white dress that I picked out of Seventeen Magazine. First came the interview portion, and that‚Äôs when the trouble started. The judges asked me about the Anita Hill testimony; I wasn‚Äôt ready for that. I was ready for world peace. They were supposed to ask me about my goals, so I could say world peace. But that didn‚Äôt happen. The talent portion was later that night at the homecoming dance. The whole school was there. I chose a Sheena Easton song; poor choice. Not the right crowd for that. The other girl chose ‚ÄòI Feel Good‚Äô by Stephanie Mills, and she had the whole crowd singing along. That‚Äôs when I knew it was over. But then, a miracle. The guidance counselor quieted everyone down, and announced the winner: it was me. Me! It was my Kelly Kapowski moment. Everyone was cheering, the other girl congratulated me. But it only lasted five seconds, because the guidance counselor said: ‚ÄòWait a second, I‚Äôm sorry. Joanna is the runner-up.‚Äô It was the worst moment of my life. In fact, the only thing that got me through COVID was knowing that it could not possibly, possibly be worse than that moment. And here‚Äôs a twist for you. Remember that guidance counselor? Several years later I ended up acting alongside his son in a play at Queens College. In one scene I pulled a gun on him, and the director was like: ‚ÄòWe need more anger. Think about something that makes you angry.‚Äô I was like: ‚ÄòWell, that‚Äôs easy. His father ruined my senior year. And quite possibly, my entire life.‚Äù
